$q3 = Formula("2/1+2/4+2/9");

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
\{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
$PAR
Note that
\(\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{n^2}\)
converges to \(\frac{\pi^2}{6}.\)
What does
\(\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \left(\frac{1}{n^2} + \frac{1}{(n+1)^2}\right)\)
converge to.  Type "pi" for \(\pi\) and use DNE if it doesn't converge.
$BR
END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

$q4 = Formula("((pi^2)/3)-1");

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
\{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
$PAR
The series
\(\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{n}{n^3+n-1}\)
behaves like the \(p\)-series for what \(p\)?
$BR
\(p={}\)
END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

$q5 = Formula("2");

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
\{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
$BR
(By "behaves like," we mean that for very large \(n,\) the terms of the series
get relatively close to a constant multiple of the terms of some \(p\)-series.)
$PAR
The series
\(\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{n^2}{n^3+n-1}\)
behaves like the \(p\)-series for what \(p\)?
$BR
\(p={}\)
END_TEXT
